WEBVTT

00:00.000 --> 00:05.560
All righty, what is your name and what are you doing here? My name is Apoorva Somani and I'm one of the Red Team reviewers this

00:05.560 --> 00:07.560
year. Oh, awesome.

00:07.860 --> 00:13.080
What, you created this competition and now you're back to be a part of the Foundation Society. Why?

00:14.560 --> 00:17.920
Because I saw what it did for me. I gave me an opportunity to

00:18.560 --> 00:24.160
study engineering and kind of come from a background where that might not necessarily be the route I would otherwise take.

00:24.520 --> 00:27.200
I go to school now at the Air Force Academy and

00:28.160 --> 00:32.680
the rising sophomore and had I not found this competition and been introduced to

00:33.080 --> 00:36.960
engineers here and meeting all these people, I wouldn't be where I am today.

00:36.960 --> 00:40.840
So that's the reason I'm here. Try and get back any way I can and volunteer and

00:41.840 --> 00:46.280
that's pretty much it. It's awesome. What are some of the things you learned in this competition like

00:46.600 --> 00:54.000
specifically that helped you in the Air Force Academy? Yeah, so one of the things that's unique about us is that we're training to become officers, right?

00:54.040 --> 00:57.920
So things like leadership, things like working in this kind of team dynamics.

00:57.920 --> 01:04.400
I can realize now looking back what a horrible leader I was in some of these competitions, some of the mistakes I made,

01:04.740 --> 01:10.680
right? The way I yelled at people or spoke to people and then it's like now as I come along you kind of grow with the

01:10.680 --> 01:17.880
competition. So I started my freshman year and then step by step you learn what it actually means as you like grow within it and

01:17.880 --> 01:23.640
take on more positions. And then now looking back, it's like everything I know about leadership, everything

01:23.640 --> 01:29.760
I know about working in these crazy teams with all these talented people, it's just like taking care of your people, right?

01:29.760 --> 01:35.120
So like when we, I've never actually won ISSTC, but like when we lose, right? It's not about yourself.

01:35.120 --> 01:40.360
It's not about how bad you feel. You have to take care of everybody around you, right? Because it's a huge loss for everyone.

01:40.360 --> 01:42.360
Everyone worked hard to get here.

01:42.360 --> 01:46.400
Everyone like suffered away for 60 hours and you have to take care of your people.

01:46.400 --> 01:51.320
So that's one of the huge things that I'm definitely taking in to heart as I continue with my military career.

01:51.560 --> 01:58.760
How did you work your way up the ladder from being maybe just a part of the competition to being a leader to now being on the red team? Like how did you?

01:58.760 --> 02:11.160
Yeah, so I think one thing that everyone needs to apply is that if you might think that, oh, that's not for me and you don't really know that unless you put yourself in uncomfortable situations, right?

02:11.160 --> 02:20.800
So I started out as just a number of ops and then that year at ISSTC, I went for system engineer, which is kind of like one of the leadership roles between the departments.

02:20.920 --> 02:28.920
And I was horrible. I didn't know what I was doing and we lost pretty horribly, but it's like you won't get that experience and you won't improve.

02:28.920 --> 02:31.760
You don't just throw yourself off a life raft, right?

02:31.760 --> 02:37.560
And if you really want to like just see what you're made of, see what you can do, you have to do that, right?

02:37.560 --> 02:48.920
I think like with red team and all these things, there's like a natural progression for me where instead of CEOing, I really liked getting to bounce around and work with all the teams, all the departments still,

02:48.920 --> 02:58.200
but kind of in more of like an advisory role and just really critique them and make fun of them the way I was made fun of and that's just how it worked out for me.

02:58.200 --> 03:01.160
Can you explain like what red team is to somebody who doesn't know?

03:01.160 --> 03:09.600
Yeah, so red team is basically one of the final reviews that we have and it's, again, everything in this competition is based off of real industry experiences, right?

03:09.600 --> 03:15.840
So this is something that will actually happen when you're eventually part of a company working on one of these proposals.

03:15.840 --> 03:25.440
You'll have a final review, like an internal review where people are basically going to ask you every little nook and cranny of your proposal, what's wrong with it, why won't it work, all these things.

03:25.440 --> 03:33.320
So it's a final check before you present in front of your real NASA engineers, your real astronauts that we have this year.

03:33.320 --> 03:40.000
So it's just a final check and then we're also like just here helping out and anything that we can do.

03:40.000 --> 03:40.800
Awesome, thank you.

